value.value: A measurement of the total number of induced abortions experienced by a female subject.
A measurement of the total number of pregnancy events experienced by the female subject prior to the current pregnancy.
A measurement of the total number of spontaneous abortions (in which the fetus is less than 20 weeks gestational age) experienced by a female subject.
Blood present in the umbilical arteries at the time of delivery.
The extracellular fluid component found in the spaces between tissues. This excludes plasma and transcellular fluid.
Blood present in the umbilical vein at the time of delivery.
A type of control using different doses or regimens of the same treatment (fixed dose) among the study groups. [From ICH E10].
A study that assesses an agent's ability to provoke an immune response (humoral and/or cell-mediated) in the subject.
A unit of mass commonly used to express the molar mass of a substance in milligram(s) per mole.
A mass unit equal to one kilogram used as a denominator to build a derived unit expressed as a ratio.

label.value: 50 Percent Cell Culture Infective Dose per Milliliter

value.value: A potency unit equal to the potency at which one milliliter of preparation contains one 50 percent cell culture infective dose.
A unit of radioactive decay expressed in atoms of radioactive material that decay over a period of time equal to sixty seconds in a volume unit equal to a half milliliter.

label.value: 50 Percent Embryo Infective Dose per Milliliter

value.value: A potency unit for measuring infectious activity of a biologic product or an infectious agent preparation equal to the potency at which one milliliter of infectious material contains one 50 percent embryo infective dose.
Unit of arbitrary substance concentration (biologic activity concentration) defined as the concentration of one international unit per one deciliter of system volume.
A unit of measure equal to kilograms per length unit equal to one centimeter.

label.value: Spot Forming Units Per Million Peripheral Blood Mononuclear Cells

value.value: A unit of measure equal to the spot forming units per million cells.
An arbitrary unit of substance concentration expressed in milligrams per a volume of hydrogen peroxide. One Carratelli unit is equal to 0.8mg substance per liter of hydrogen peroxide.
A concentration unit equal to one micromole of solute in one liter of solution per unit of time equal to one minute.
Having characteristics of chronic disease superimposed with areas of acute (active) disease.
An excessively sharp or violent acute episode.
A disease characteristic falling between acute and chronic, but predominantly acute.
A disease characteristic falling between acute and chronic, but predominantly chronic.
A finding that generally has features of focal and multifocal distribution.
Being widespread throughout a specific area.
A supernumerary tissue in addition to normal tissues.
A state characterized by the gradual increase in entities or substances.
Any disease or disorder of a gland, characterized by abnormal development or enlargement of the gland.
A finding of dysplasia in the adnexal appendages.

Increase in eosinophilic cytoplasmic droplets of alpha 2u-globulin in the S2 segment of the proximal tubules in the cortex with exfoliation of cells, an increase in mitotic figures in affected portions of the proximal tubules, tubular basophilia in some cases, and formation of granular casts at the junction of the inner and outer stripes of the medulla. (INHAND)
A congenital abnormality resulting in the absence of an anatomical structure.
Reactive astrocytic proliferation often associated with degenerative, inflammatory or neoplastic changes in the central nervous system.
Abnormally large, misshapen and/or clumped vacuoles containing cell debris in the testis, or present in stages of spermatogenesis when not normally seen.
Confirmatory presence of bacterial microorganisms.
Intracytoplasmic phagolysosomes that are strongly basophilic. These structures are usually seen within the tubular epithelium and glomeruli of the kidney in response to antisense oligonucleotides.
An accumulation of cell fragments.
A finding of an empty space in a histological section of paraffin-embedded tissue created by the dissolution of cholesterol crystals.
The dissolution of chromatin in a cell.

A spontaneous, age-related renal disease of rats, characterized by morphological changes such as degeneration of the epithelium lining of the tubules, thickening of glomerular, Bowman and proximal tubular basement membranes, and lesions in the glomeruli leading to mesangial overload and glomerulosclerosis.
A hard covering or layer of solid matter formed by dried bodily exudate or secretion.
A finding that generally has features of degeneration and atrophy.
A finding that generally has features of degeneration and necrosis.
A finding that generally has features of degeneration and regeneration.
A pathophysiological process characterized by the dilatation or expansion of a hollow, tubular tissue or organ.
Degenerative changes in elastic tissues.
A change or slight modification in the epithelial cells along the respiratory tract.
